This paper deals with the optimization of memory usage in Tardos's fingerprinting codes, which are used for digital content protection. This topic falls under the category of computer security (cs.CR) as well as information theory (cs.IT). The paper also involves the use of algorithms and data structures to optimize memory usage, which falls under the category of data structures (cs.DS) and computational complexity (cs.CC). Finally, the paper discusses practical issues such as approximation errors, which could fall under the category of multimedia (cs.MM) if the digital content being protected is multimedia content.
